I made the prediction base on past postseason records from 2015 until now. 
This year is Chicago's second time in postseason. They got 3rd place in American league in regular season, and they are facing Houston this round, which is a strong team. So I don't think they have very great chance to win the world series.
Houston is a strong team, it showed up in every postseason from 2015 until now, except 2016, entered 3 final championship, and won 2 of them.
Los Angeles is also a strong team. It entered all postseason since 2015, entered 3 final championship, and won 1.
Milwaukee entered 3 postseason three times, and entered national league final one time, but didn't win. So it is a medium level team.
Oakland and San Diego didn't earn their seat in postseason this year. So there just 0 percent chance
San Francisco is also a weak team, showed up 2 times in postseason, but it has 1st place in national league this year in regular season, so it has higher chance than Chicago.
Tampa Bay entered postseason three time, and final one times since 2015. And it has 1st place this year in American League It's also a strong team.
There are another two team currently in postseason, Boston and Atlanta. They both entered postseason three times, and Boston had won one championship, so I expect 8% and 2% respectively.
I am not very familiar with baseball, LA Dodgers, Houston Astros and San Francisco Giants are the three which I only know about. So I give them about 80% total for win.

While the Dodgers must play a wild card game, I believe that their experience as defending World Champions, playing in the World Series three out of the past four years, as well as their late season acquisitions of Max Scherzer and Trea Turner, arguably the best pitcher and best hitter in the MLB, that they most likely to win the World Series this year.

There is a great degree of bias in my decision-making. I am a huge Dodger fan and also they were the World Series Champs last year, so, *knock on wood* the Dodgers are my #1 pick. Additionally, I can't bear to select anyone else on this list, especially the SF Giants.
LA Dodgers are on the top by ranking so they have a better chance of winning

I distributed based largely on their overall records. The A's have been on a losing streak, and the Padre's performance has been too low, so I put them both at zero. And I reserved a chunk for "another team" because there isn't a drastic fall-off in performance after the top six performers, all of which are listed here. Then I checked the crowd forecast and lowered my number #4-6 choices by two percent each, and raised "another team" by six, since I don't know much about baseball.

Based on average word series odds from playoff status, 538, fangraphs, and baseball reference. I favor the Giants over the Dodgers because they don't have to play in the wild card.

The Giants are the favorites with a first-place berth and a great second-half record. The Dodgers are the best second-half team in baseball, but their chances are shrunk by being a wild card team. Most of the other teams have roughly equal odds.
Rays easily win the AL then 50:50 in the final.

The crowd is (currently) overestimating the Dodgers. Don't get me wrong... they are a blockbuster powerhouse with grade A talent and deep pockets... but with the wild card race looming, both the Giants and the Dodgers have a potential uphill slog ahead of them... with a one game play-off the favors luck more than talent. 
Also, don't count out the Padres just yet... they put up a heck of a fight and have MVP talent giving the best of the best headaches. It isn't uncommon for a wild card team to go on an October magic tear. 
With ~9 games to go, this is an exciting time to watch.
I feel good about this... for now.
